}}\n* Macedonian: {{tt|mk|ноти|f-p}}, {{tt|mk|партиту́ра|f}} {{qualifier|continental Normandy}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{tt|nb|noter|p}}\n* Portuguese: {{tt+|pt|partitura|f}}\n* Romanian: {{tt+|ro|partitură|f}}\n* Russian: {{tt+|ru|но́ты|f-p}}, {{tt+|ru|партиту́ра|f}}c\n* Scottish Gaelic: {{tt|gd|ceòl|m}}\n* Slovak: {{tt|sk|noty|f-p}}, {{tt|sk|hudobnina|f}}\n* Spanish: {{tt+|es|música|f}}\n}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* Alabama: {{t-check|akz|olaachi}}\n* Azerbaijani: {{t+check|az|not}}, {{t+check|az|musiqi}}\n* Bengali: {{t+check|bn|বাজনা}}\n* Breton: {{t-check|br|sonerezh|m}}, {{t-check|br|muzik|m}}\n* Chamorro: {{t-check|ch|música}}, {{t-check|ch|dandan}}\n* Gilbertese: {{t-check|gil|te katangitang}}\n* Haitian Creole: {{t-check|ht|mizik}}\n* Hiligaynon: {{t-check|hil|lanton}}\n* Hindi: {{t-check|hi|संगीत विद्या|m}}, {{t+check|hi|संगीत|m}}, {{t+check|hi|राग|m}}, {{t+check|hi|लय|f}}, {{t+check|hi|ताल|m}}, {{t+check|hi|सुर|m}}, {{t+check|hi|सुस्वर|?}}, {{t-check|hi|तालैक्य|?}}\n* Icelandic: {{t+check|is|tónlist}}\n* Interlingua: {{t-check|ia|musica}}\n* Latin: {{t-check|la|mūsica|f}}\n* Latvian: {{t-check|lv|mūzika|f}}\n* Low German:\n*: Dutch Low Saxon: {{t-check|nds-nl|meziek|?}}\n* Luganda: {{t-check|lg|ennyimba|c9|c10}}\n* Macedonian: {{t+check|mk|музика|f}}\n* Malagasy: {{t+check|mg|mozika}}\n* Malay: {{t+check|ms|dendang}}\n* Malayalam: {{t+check|ml|സംഗീതം}}\n* Maltese: {{t-check|mt|mużika|f}}\n* Marathi: {{t-check|mr|संगीत|?}}\n* Old English: {{t-check|ang|drēam|m}} {{attention|ang|2=was \"[[dream#Old English|drēam]]\" - assumed inflected form or vocalised spelling; please verify if linking is acceptable. see [[User:Kephir/gadgets/xte#Translation_fixing]]}}\n* Persian: {{t-check|fa|آهنگ|tr=âhang}}, {{t+check|fa|خنیا|tr=xoniyâ}}\n* Serbo-Croatian:\n*: Cyrillic: {{t-check|sh|гла̀зба|f}}, {{t-check|sh|му̀зика|f}}\n*: Latin: {{t+check|sh|glàzba|f}}, {{t+check|sh|mùzika|f}}\n* Telugu: {{t+check|te|సంగీతం}}\n* Thai: {{t+check|th|ดนตรี|tr=dondtree}}\n* Turkish: {{t+check|tr|müzik}}\n* Yiddish: {{t-check|yi|מוזיק|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Verb===\n{{en-verb|~s|~king|~ked}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[seduce]] or [[entice]] with music.\n\n===Adjective===\n{{en-adj}}\n\n# {{lb|en|rare}} [[musical|Musical]].<ref>{{R:OED Online|entry=music|pos=''n.'' and ''adj.''|noformat=1|id=7569208909}}</ref>\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:Theophilus Gale|T[heophilus] G[ale]]]|title=The Court of the Gentiles: or A Discourse Touching the Original of Human Literature, Both Philologie and Philosophie, from the Scriptures, and Jewish Church in Order to a Demonstration,{{nb...|of 1. The Perfection of Gods VVord, and Church Light. 2: The Imperfection of Natures Light, and Mischief of Vain Philosophie. 3. The Right Use of Human Learning, and Especially Sound Philosophie.}}|volume_plain=part I (Of Philologie)|location=Oxon [Oxford]|publisher={{...|Printed by}} Hen[ry] Hall for Tho[mas] Gilbert|year=1669|pages=136–137|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/bim_early-english-books-1641-1700_the-court-of-the-gentile_gale-theophilus_1669/page/137/mode/1up|passage=Again, ''Moſes'' was the firſt that brought in ''ſacred Muſick'': thus in like manner ''Strabo lib''. 10. 453. informes us, that the ''Bacchick Muſick'' was famous throughout ''Aſia''; and that many '''''muſick''' Inſtruments'' had obteined a ''Barbarick name'', as ''Jambla'', ''Sambuke'', ''Barbitos'', ''Magades'', &c. which ſeem all to be of ''Hebrew origination''.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=w:Jones Very|chapter=The Unrevealed|editor=Helen R. Deese|title=Jones Very: The Complete Poems|location=Athens, Ga.|publisher=w:University of Georgia Press|start_month=fall|start_year=1838|month=summer|year=1839|year_published=1993|page=159|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/jonesverycomplet0000very/page/159/mode/1up|lines=4–9|isbn=0-8203-1481-1|passage=Loosened / Thy tongue shall with sweet-flowing sounds surprize / The ear of sense; another than thyself / Will be seen within to have come, and bringing / '''Music''' tones from other spheres to have made / Thee ever the harp of hidden minstrelsy.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|author=[[w:William Ellery Channing (poet)|William Ellery Channing]]|chapter=The Desert|title=Poems|volume_plain=second series|location=Boston, Mass.|publisher=James Munroe and Company|year=1847|page=59|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/poems00chan/page/59/mode/1up|passage=So should she drape the World’s wide round, / With sunny robes, and fresh Spring weather / And consecrate the loneliest ground, / While we went wandering linked together, / Her '''music''' voice, her beaming eyes, / Give to the Silence, glad replies.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|author=[[w:Sarah Josepha Hale|Sarah J[osepha] Hale]]|title=The Judge; a Drama of American Life|editor=Sarah J[osepha] Hale|journal=[[w:Godey's Lady's Book|Godey’s Lady’s Book]]|volume=XLII|location=Philadelphia, Pa.|publisher=[[w:Louis Antoine Godey|L[ouis] A[ntoine] Godey]]|month=January|year=1851|section=act I, scene III|page=26|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/GodeySMagazine1851/page/n46/mode/1up|column=2|passage=And therefore, prisoner, you are doomed for life / To solitary toil. Alone! alone! alone! / Love’s '''music''' voice will never greet your ear; / Affection’s eye will never meet your gaze; / Nor heart-warm hand of friend return your grasp; / But morn, and noon, and night, days, months, and years, / Will all be told in this one word—alone!}}\n\n===See also===\n* {{pedia|Definition of music}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20050903200746/http://www.musicnovatory.com/ MusicNovatory: the science of music encyclopedia]\n* [[:Category:Music]]\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Century 1911}}\n* {{R:OneLook}}\n<references/>\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=cimsu|MICUs}}\n\n{{C|en|Music}}\n\n==Interlingua==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|ia|[ˈmuzik]}}\n\n===Adjective===\n{{ia-adj}}\n\n# [[musical]], of, or pertaining to music.\n\n====Synonyms====\n* {{l|ia|musical}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|musike}}"}}